1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,250
You're listening to: Postgres Index Bloat Nearly Took Down Production: A VACUUM Deep-Dive.

2
00:00:06,250 --> 00:00:13,088
A table that was 2 GB of data carried 14 GB of dead tuples and bloated indexes.

3
00:00:13,088 --> 00:00:24,783
How MVCC creates bloat, how to measure it, and how autovacuum tuning, HOT updates, and a careful REINDEX brought query times back from 3s to 40ms.

4
00:00:24,783 --> 00:00:25,853
Let's get started.

5
00:00:25,853 --> 00:00:30,600
Our lab_results table held about 2 GB of actual data.

6
00:00:30,600 --> 00:00:35,096
On disk, it and its indexes occupied 31 GB.

7
00:00:35,096 --> 00:00:40,216
Queries that used to return in 40ms were creeping past 3 seconds.

8
00:00:40,216 --> 00:00:44,254
Nothing in the schema had changed; the row count had barely grown.

9
00:00:44,254 --> 00:00:49,122
The disk was just... filling up, and the database was getting slower in lockstep.

10
00:00:49,122 --> 00:00:55,913
The culprit was bloat — and understanding it means understanding how PostgreSQL handles updates under the hood.

11
00:00:55,913 --> 00:00:59,459
This is the deep-dive I wish I'd read before the incident.

12
00:00:59,459 --> 00:01:06,682
For the broader scaling picture, pair it with database sharding & partitioning and PostgreSQL performance optimization.

13
00:01:06,682 --> 00:01:10,997
Now, let's talk about Why Postgres creates dead rows: MVCC.

14
00:01:10,997 --> 00:01:18,257
PostgreSQL uses MVCC (Multi-Version Concurrency Control) so that readers never block writers.

15
00:01:18,257 --> 00:01:22,475
The trick: when you UPDATE a row, Postgres does not overwrite it.

16
00:01:22,475 --> 00:01:28,004
It writes a new version of the row and marks the old version as dead (a "dead tuple").

17
00:01:28,004 --> 00:01:34,002
Transactions that started before the update still see the old version; new ones see the new version.

18
00:01:34,002 --> 00:01:36,742
A DELETE similarly just marks the row dead.

19
00:01:36,742 --> 00:01:44,182
This is brilliant for concurrency and terrible if you ignore it, because those dead tuples don't disappear on their own.

20
00:01:44,182 --> 00:01:47,319
Every update to a row leaves a corpse behind.

21
00:01:47,319 --> 00:01:55,300
Our lab_results table got a status update several times per result — each one creating a new live tuple and a dead one.

22
00:01:55,300 --> 00:02:02,656
Multiply by millions of results and you get 14 GB of dead tuples sitting in a 2 GB table.

23
00:02:02,656 --> 00:02:05,817
The mechanism that reclaims this space is VACUUM.

24
00:02:05,817 --> 00:02:07,992
Moving on to Measuring the damage.

25
00:02:07,992 --> 00:02:10,024
Before touching anything, measure.

26
00:02:10,024 --> 00:02:15,324
This query shows dead-tuple counts and the last (auto)vacuum time per table:

27
00:02:15,324 --> 00:02:25,360
Ours showed lab_results with a dead_ratio near 7 — seven dead tuples for every live one — and a last_autovacuum of three weeks ago.

28
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:31,237
Autovacuum, the background process that is supposed to clean this up, had effectively stopped keeping up.

29
00:02:31,237 --> 00:02:35,336
For index bloat specifically, pgstattuple gives the truth:

30
00:02:35,336 --> 00:02:43,221
Our primary index was at ~22% leaf density — meaning ~78% of the index pages were wasted space.

31
00:02:43,221 --> 00:02:49,927
That is why query times had quadrupled: every index scan was reading four times more pages than it needed to.

32
00:02:49,927 --> 00:02:52,836
Next up: Why autovacuum fell behind.

33
00:02:52,836 --> 00:02:58,221
Autovacuum is triggered per-table when dead tuples exceed a threshold:

34
00:02:58,221 --> 00:03:05,877
The default scale_factor is 0.2 — autovacuum only kicks in after 20% of the table is dead.

35
00:03:05,877 --> 00:03:14,230
On a large, update-heavy table, 20% is a lot of dead tuples, and by the time autovacuum runs it has a huge amount to clean.

36
00:03:14,230 --> 00:03:23,413
Worse, our autovacuum was being throttled by conservative cost-delay settings and was getting cancelled by an ALTER/lock from a nightly job before it finished.

37
00:03:23,413 --> 00:03:26,754
Two configuration changes fixed the ongoing problem.

38
00:03:26,754 --> 00:03:31,646
I tuned them per-table rather than globally, because only a few hot tables needed it:

39
00:03:31,646 --> 00:03:37,283
Vacuuming little and often is far cheaper than vacuuming rarely and enormously.

40
00:03:37,283 --> 00:03:40,985
Let's explore Reducing bloat at the source: HOT updates.

41
00:03:40,985 --> 00:03:44,002
The best bloat is the kind you never create.

42
00:03:44,002 --> 00:03:57,512
PostgreSQL has an optimization called HOT (Heap-Only Tuple) updates: if an update does not change any indexed column, and there's room on the same page, Postgres can update the row in place without touching every index.

43
00:03:57,512 --> 00:04:01,682
HOT updates dramatically reduce both table and index bloat.

44
00:04:01,682 --> 00:04:03,040
We were defeating it.

45
00:04:03,040 --> 00:04:10,552
Our status-update query touched an indexed updated_at column on every write, so no update qualified as HOT.

46
00:04:10,552 --> 00:04:11,899
Two changes helped:

47
00:04:11,899 --> 00:04:16,550
Don't index columns that change on every write unless you truly query by them.

48
00:04:16,550 --> 00:04:19,206
We dropped an index on a high-churn column..

49
00:04:19,206 --> 00:04:24,290
Lower the table's fillfactor so each page leaves room for in-place updates:.

50
00:04:24,314 --> 00:04:31,355
A fillfactor of 85 leaves 15% of each page free for HOT updates to land in place.

51
00:04:31,355 --> 00:04:45,526
After a rewrite, the ratio of HOT updates (n_tup_hot_upd / n_tup_upd in pg_stat_user_tables) jumped from near-zero to over 90%, and bloat accumulation slowed to a crawl.

52
00:04:45,526 --> 00:04:48,506
Now let's look at Reclaiming the space already lost.

53
00:04:48,506 --> 00:04:53,735
Tuning stops new bloat; it does not shrink the 31 GB you already have.

54
00:04:53,735 --> 00:04:58,446
VACUUM marks dead space reusable but rarely returns it to the OS.

55
00:04:58,446 --> 00:05:01,307
To actually reclaim disk, you have two options:

56
00:05:01,307 --> 00:05:10,333
VACUUM FULL — fully rewrites the table compactly, but takes an ACCESS EXCLUSIVE lock (the table is unavailable for the duration).

57
00:05:10,333 --> 00:05:14,720
Fine at 3 AM on a small table; unacceptable on a hot one..

58
00:05:14,720 --> 00:05:20,934
pg_repack — rebuilds the table and indexes with only brief locking, online.

59
00:05:20,934 --> 00:05:22,172
This is what I used..

60
00:05:22,172 --> 00:05:30,982
For the indexes specifically, REINDEX INDEX CONCURRENTLY (Postgres 12+) rebuilds a bloated index without blocking writes:

61
00:05:30,982 --> 00:05:43,807
After repack + concurrent reindex, the table-plus-indexes footprint dropped from 31 GB to 2.4 GB, and the patient-lookup query went from ~3s back to ~40ms.

62
00:05:43,807 --> 00:05:45,477
Now, let's talk about Results.

63
00:05:45,477 --> 00:05:47,352
Metric, Before, After.

64
00:05:47,352 --> 00:05:53,302
On-disk size (table + indexes), 31 GB, 2.4 GB.

65
00:05:53,302 --> 00:05:57,449
Dead-tuple ratio, ~7.0, ~0.1.

66
00:05:57,449 --> 00:06:02,196
Index leaf density, ~22%, ~91%.

67
00:06:02,196 --> 00:06:07,965
Patient-lookup query, ~3,000ms, ~40ms.

68
00:06:07,965 --> 00:06:11,884
HOT update ratio, ~3%, ~92%.

69
00:06:11,884 --> 00:06:16,187
Moving on to The checklist I now run on every write-heavy table.

70
00:06:16,187 --> 00:06:22,845
Monitor n_dead_tup and last_autovacuum in pg_stat_user_tables.

71
00:06:22,845 --> 00:06:27,401
Silent autovacuum failure is the root of most bloat incidents..

72
00:06:27,401 --> 00:06:35,658
Tune autovacuum_vacuum_scale_factor per hot table (0.01–0.05), not globally..

73
00:06:35,658 --> 00:06:43,026
Protect HOT updates: don't index high-churn columns; set a fillfactor around 85 on update-heavy tables..

74
00:06:43,026 --> 00:06:47,425
Reclaim space online with pg_repack and REINDEX ...

75
00:06:47,425 --> 00:06:52,100
CONCURRENTLY, not VACUUM FULL, on anything user-facing..

76
00:06:52,100 --> 00:07:00,285
Watch long-running transactions — they hold back the "oldest visible" horizon and can prevent vacuum from removing dead tuples at all..

77
00:07:00,285 --> 00:07:09,840
Bloat is not a bug in Postgres; it is the cost of MVCC, and MVCC is why Postgres handles concurrency so gracefully.

78
00:07:09,840 --> 00:07:12,569
The job is to keep the cleanup keeping pace.

79
00:07:12,569 --> 00:07:18,939
For where to go when a single node is no longer enough, see database sharding & partitioning.

80
